<paragraph id="B2E307D943438FB875186018F51CF8A1" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Type-species.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="859CA8B673507DD89AEB5AF9C006AA79" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
<taxonomicName id="F69E51D0B3081AF881B1B8168E1458A1" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Mamestra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mamestra praecipua" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="praecipua">Mamestra praecipua</taxonomicName>
Staudinger, 1895, Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift, Gesellschaft Iris zu Dresden8: 316.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C254D81FBB91A8B5CBB57CFEB180A1A4" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="87765FB80B037D2A78161A2A7812496E" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B589FED99BEF7EFF7C08F49EE8D947D8" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
The three species belonging to this subgenus are large, robust moths with simple ochreous-brownish or purplish-blackish-brown (generally unicolorous but sometimes, individually, contrasting) colouration and regular pattern, somewhat resembling certain forms of 
<taxonomicName id="666F87B5094BE1D01387300DF1DEF0FE" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Apamea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Apamea monoglypha" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monoglypha">Apamea monoglypha</taxonomicName>
(Hufnagel, 1766).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5F9C20F0AB8A01FA69F07DB84C673D3F" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">In the male genitalia, the saccular processes are simple, short or acute, symmetrical, with prominent tuft of specialised setae on the right side. Vesica is tubular, relatively short and retroflexed, with only a short fascia of cornuti subterminally.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="49DDDB07884CF4E084C5BD9D9147D79C" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">In the female genitalia, the appendix bursae is slightly prominent only, the corpus bursae has two short longitudinal signa.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EF891718D02A8FAE08847F5A72E73167" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="47D678C7C6BE7A2AC457F646083A5B57" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3CC58D23D82F73EB2E191851723EEADF" pageId="4" pageNumber="137">
The name refers to the relative simplicity of colouration and configuration of male genitalia as opposed to the huge majority of 
<taxonomicName id="2104159F16919397C206B0DAD5C964E2" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Polia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Polia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" phylum="Nemertea" rank="genus">Polia</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C1BA0C4141FD18797592141BE1CC055D" genus="Poliina" lsidName="Poliina" pageId="4" pageNumber="137" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Poliina">Poliina</taxonomicName>
, respectively.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
